Child _ Process :
------------------------- >
>> Node.js is single-threaded and uses only one CPU core by default. For CPU-intensive tasks, this blocks the event loop and affects performance.
>> Child processes allow us to run heavy computations in separate processes, enabling parallel execution across multiple CPU cores. This improves performance and keeps the main thread responsive.
>> However, each child process consumes additional memory, so there is a trade-off between CPU utilization and RAM usage. For better efficiency, worker threads can also be used as they share memory.

# When SHOULD You Use Child Process :
✅ CPU-heavy tasks:
Image processing
Video encoding
Data compression
Large loops
Encryption

NOTE: Child processes allow Node.js to use multiple CPU cores

> The node js child process,  has 4 method's there are:
1) exec, 
2) fork, 
3) spawn, 
4) execFile

why child process needs to us:
>> Node's event loop runs on 1 CPU core. Heavy sync code blocks ALL requests — one user's image resize hangs every other user's API call.
>> And in order to handle the main issues: 
1) Image resizing / thumbnail generation
2) Video transcoding (FFmpeg)
3) PDF generation / report building
4) Parallel data processing pipelines
5) Running tests in isolation

